"Thomas Ledig F., Rehfeldt G.E., Sáenz-Romero C., Flores-López C.","Projections of suitable habitat for rare species under global warming scenarios",2010,"American Journal of Botany","97","6",,"970","987",,,10.3732/ajb.0900329,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77953511819&partnerID=40&md5=8be7938e7953c0f94be60d4ec2f8f8b6","Institute of Forest Genetics, Pacific Southwest Research Station, USDA Forest Service, 2480 Carson Road, Placerville, CA 95667, United States; Forestry Sciences Laboratory, Rocky Mountain Research Station, USDA Forest Service, 1221 S. Main, Moscow, Idaho 83843, United States; Instituto de Investigaciones Agropecuarias y Forestales, Universidad Michoacana de San Nicolás de Hidalgo (IIAF-UMSNH), Km 9.5 Carretera Morelia-Zinapécuaro, Tarímbaro, Michoacán 58880, Mexico; Departamento Forestal, Universidad Autónoma Agraria Antonio Narro, Buenavista, Saltillo, Coahuila 25000, Mexico; Department of Plant Sciences, University of California, Placerville, CA 95667, United States","Thomas Ledig, F., Institute of Forest Genetics, Pacific Southwest Research Station, USDA Forest Service, 2480 Carson Road, Placerville, CA 95667, United States, Department of Plant Sciences, University of California, Placerville, CA 95667, United States; Rehfeldt, G.E., Forestry Sciences Laboratory, Rocky Mountain Research Station, USDA Forest Service, 1221 S. Main, Moscow, Idaho 83843, United States; Sáenz-Romero, C., Instituto de Investigaciones Agropecuarias y Forestales, Universidad Michoacana de San Nicolás de Hidalgo (IIAF-UMSNH), Km 9.5 Carretera Morelia-Zinapécuaro, Tarímbaro, Michoacán 58880, Mexico; Flores-López, C., Departamento Forestal, Universidad Autónoma Agraria Antonio Narro, Buenavista, Saltillo, Coahuila 25000, Mexico","Premise of the study: Modeling the contemporary and future climate niche for rare plants is a major hurdle in conservation, yet such projections are necessary to prevent extinctions that may result from climate change.Methods: We used recently developed spline climatic models and modifi ed Random Forests statistical procedures to predict suitable habitats of three rare, endangered spruces of Mexico and a spruce of the southwestern USA. We used three general circulation models and two sets of carbon emission scenarios (optimistic and pessimistic) for future climates.Key results: Our procedures predicted present occurrence perfectly. For the decades 2030, 2060, and 2090, the ranges of all taxa progressively decreased, to the point of transient disappearance for one species in the decade 2060 but reappearance in 2090. Contrary to intuition, habitat did not develop to the north for any of the Mexican taxa; rather, climate niches for two taxa re-materialized several hundred kilometers southward in the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt. The climate niche for a third Mexican taxon shrank drastically, and its two mitotypes responded differently, one of the first demonstrations of the importance of intraspecifi c genetic variation in climate niches. The climate niche of the U.S. species shrank northward and upward in elevation.Conclusion: The results are important for conservation of these species and are of general signifi cance for conservation by assisted colonization. We conclude that our procedures for producing models and projecting the climate niches of Mexican spruces provide a way for handling other rare plants, which constitute the great bulk of the world' s endangered and most vulnerable flora. © 2010 Botanical Society of America.","Assisted colonization; Climatic models; Conservation; Picea engelmannii; Picea martinezii; Picea mexicana; Random forests algorithm; Trans-mexican volcanic belt","algorithm; carbon emission; climate modeling; colonization; coniferous tree; conservation genetics; extinction; general circulation model; genetic variation; global warming; habitat quality; prediction; rare species; species conservation; volcanic belt; Mexico [North America]; United States; Picea; Picea e